diff:1617641818:1617641818:=1,89d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Grammatical Structure of Singaporean English%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: yuluz%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Singaporean English, or Singlish, is sprinkled with Chinese, Hokkien and Malay phrases and their different grammatical structures. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c As a multiracial and multicultural society, Singapore has a very diverse linguistic scene. Due to its large population of Chinese, Malay and Indian descendents and its British colonial root, the country has four official languages: English, Mandarin, Malay, and Tamil. %0a%3c %0a%3c It cultural and linguistic diversity have resulted in an informal, localized form of English known as Singlish, which is infused with many characteristics of the other languages spoken in the area. As a result, grammatical constructions of Singlish are very different from standard English.%0a%3c %0a%3c The most noticeable difference is Singlish's prevalent use of functional particles at the end of a clause. The particles are borrowed from Southern Chinese dialects, most notably Hokkien. When people attach different particles to the same clause, the meaning would change. Here is a set of examples which all have the structure of "can + particle" but have different underlying meanings:%0a%3c %0a%3c     1. "Can meh" (Can I do this?/Can this be done? - in an unsure/doubtful tone)%0a%3c     2. "Can lah" (Alright you can do this/this can be done - in a soft, sometimes dismissing tone)%0a%3c     3. "Can hor" (I think I can do this/this can be done but i need your confirmation)%0a%3c %0a%3c Maybe as you can already tell from the above examples, in Singlish people tend to drop the subject of a sentence and we often have to infer it through the context. This is very similar to the structure of Mandarin. Here are some more examples:%0a%3c %0a%3c     1."Don’t want lah” (I don't want this.) %0a%3c     2."Eh, got free time this afternoon or not?" (Do you have free time this afternoon?)%0a%3c %0a%3c While sometimes Singlish speakers drop the subject, at other times they drop the verb, especially when a sentence has the structure of "subject + be + ...". Examples are as follows:%0a%3c %0a%3c     1. I scared. (I am scared/I was scared. - the tense really depends on the context)%0a%3c     2. Your drink there. (Your drink is there.)%0a%3c     3. I eating now. (I am eating now.)%0a%3c %0a%3c These are just some instances of how Singlish grammatical constructions are different from standard American English. You can learn more on the topic by going to this link: https://etoninstitute.com/blog/5-unique-features-singlish, or just google Singlish online. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: C:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
